Title : Johann Fück
Text : '''Johann Wilhelm Fück''' (born {{Birth date|1894|7|8}} in [[Frankfurt am Main]]; died {{Death date|1974|11|24}} in [[Halle (Saale)|Halle]]) was a [[German people|German]] [[Orientalism|Orientalist]].

Starting in 1913, Fück studied classical and Semitic [[philology]] at [[Martin Luther University of Halle-Wittenberg]] and [[Goethe University Frankfurt]]. From 1919 to 1921 he was a member of the [[German National People's Party]].<ref>Harry Waibel: ''Diener vieler Herren : Ehemalige NS-Funktionäre in der SBZ/DDR.'' Lang, Frankfurt am Main 2011 {{ISBN|978-3-631-63542-1}}, p. 96.</ref>  His promotion took place in 1921 as part of the Orientalist Seminar at Goethe University Frankfurt, where he had lectureships in [[Hebrew language]] from 1921 to 1930, and in Arabic philology and [[Islamic studies]] from 1935 to 1938. He attained his [[Habilitation#Germany|habilitation]] in 1929. In the interim from 1930 to 1935, he was a professor at the [[University of Dhaka]], Bangladesh. In 1938 Fück went back to [[Martin Luther University of Halle-Wittenberg]] where he remained until his retirement in 1962. In Halle he was also the director of the library of the [[Deutsche Morgenländische Gesellschaft]] (German Oriental Society).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ende |first=Werner |title=Johann W. Fück (1894—1974) |pages=193–195 |journal=Der Islam |volume=53 |issue=2 |date=July 1976 |url=http://www.freidok.uni-freiburg.de/volltexte/3482/pdf/Ende_Johann_W._Fueck.pdf}}</ref>

Along with [[Karl Vollers]] and [[Régis Blachère]], Fück was an important early researcher into the language of the [[Quran]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Donner |first=Fred M. |chapter=The Qur'ān in recent scholarship: Challenges and desiderata |editor-last=Reynolds |editor-first=Gabriel Said |title=The Qur'ān in Its Historical Context |publisher=Routledge |year=2008 |page=4 |ref=harv}}</ref>

